1 On page 1 of the printed bill, line 3, after “2025” insert “, and section 23,
2 chapter , Oregon Laws 2026 (Enrolled House Bill 4066)”.
3 After line 17, insert:
4 “SECTION 2a. Notwithstanding section 21, chapter , Oregon
5 Laws 2026 (Enrolled House Bill 4066) (amending section 3, chapter 195,
6 Oregon Laws 2025), if House Bill 4066 becomes law, section 3, chapter
7 195, Oregon Laws 2025, is repealed by section 2 of this 2026 Act.”.
8 On page 2, after line 31, insert:
9 “SECTION 3a. If House Bill 4066 becomes law, section 3 of this 2026
10 Act (amending ORS 459.488) is repealed and ORS 459.488, as amended
11 by section 2, chapter 195, Oregon Laws 2025, and section 22, chapter
12 , Oregon Laws 2026 (Enrolled House Bill 4066), is amended to
13 read:
14 “459.488. ORS 459.485 does not apply to:
15 “(1) A lamp used for image capture and projection, including photocopy-
16 ing, printing, directly or in preprocessing, lithography, film and video
17 projection and holography.
18 “(2) A lamp that has a high proportion of ultraviolet light emission and
19 is one of the following:
20 “(a) A lamp with high ultraviolet content that has ultraviolet power

1 greater than two milliwatts per kilolumen.
2 “(b) A lamp for germicidal use, such as the destruction of DNA
3 (deoxyribonucleic acid), that emits a peak radiation of approximately 253.7
4 nanometers.
5 “(c) A lamp used for disinfection or fly trapping from which either:
6 “(A) The radiation power emitted between 250 and 315 nanometers re-
7 presents at least five percent of the total radiation power emitted between
8 250 and 800 nanometers; or
9 “(B) The radiation power emitted between 315 and 400 nanometers re-
10 presents at least 20 percent of the total radiation power emitted between 250
11 and 800 nanometers.
12 “(d) A lamp used for the generation of ozone where the primary purpose
13 is to emit radiation at approximately 185.1 nanometers.
14 “(e) A lamp used for coral zooxanthellae symbiosis from which the radi-
15 ation power emitted between 400 and 480 nanometers represents at least 40
16 percent of the total radiation power emitted between 250 and 800 nanometers.
17 “(f) Any lamp used in an electronic product designed to incorporate one
18 or more ultraviolet lamps and intended for irradiation of any part of the
19 living human body by ultraviolet radiation, with wavelengths in air between
20 200 and 400 nanometers, to induce skin tanning.
21 “(3) A lamp used in a medical device or otherwise used for medical or
22 veterinary diagnosis or treatment.
23 “(4) A lamp used in pharmaceutical product manufacturing or quality
24 control.
25 “(5) A lamp used for spectroscopy and photometric applications, including
26 ultraviolet-visible spectroscopy, molecular spectroscopy, atomic absorption
27 spectroscopy, nondispersive infrared (NDIR), Fourier transform infrared
28 (FTIR), medical analysis, ellipsometry, layer thickness measurement, process
29 monitoring or environmental monitoring.
30 “(6) A lamp used by academic or research institutions exclusively for
